Prykeb  Joseph McKennab  Daniel O’Reillya a Department of Chemistry, Imperial College London, South  b Division of Chemistry, School of Life Sciences, University of  Dedicated to Dr. Alfred Bader on the occasion of his 93rd birth- day and in memory of Oxana Bennett Over  the  years  domino  reactions  have  been  developed as powerful methods for the efficient synthesis of complex molecules,  often  of  biological  interest.1  Domino  reactions entail at least two consecutive bond-forming or bond-rear- rangement  reactions  where  each  following  reaction  relies on  the  chemistry  involved  in  the  preceding  step.2  These time-resolved sequences3 can be designed by carefully eval- uating the functional group reactivity in the starting mate- rials,  and  as  such  they  can  be  initiated  using  a  variety  of techniques,  including  photochemistry,4  radical  chemistry,5 metal catalysis,6 organocatalysis,7 and thermolysis.8,9 Given the  importance  of  aromatic  polyfunctional  arrays  in  the chemical industries, we sought to develop new domino pro- cesses for the preparation of the aforementioned ring sys- tems. Received: 18.09.2017 Accepted after revision: 13.10.2017 Published online: 27.11.2017 DOI: 10.1055/s-0036-1590952; Art ID: ss-2017-z0606-fa Abstract  A domino reaction has been used for the construction of lac- tonamycin derivatives. This research led to a comparison study between palladium-mediated  cascade  cyclisations  and  thermal  alkyne  [2+2+2] cyclisations. A palladium-mediated cyclisation of alkenyl bromides with alkynes  and  furans  has  been  shown  to  furnish  highly  substituted  aro- matic rings. Penta- and hexasubstituted aromatic rings have also been prepared by the thermolysis of suitably substituted alkynes under mi- crowave conditions. Tetrasubstituted pyridines can also be prepared us- ing nitriles instead of alkynes. This work will provide a new and interest- ing array of drug templates; mechanistic details are discussed for both reaction series. Key words  alkynes, aromatic rings, cyclisation, thermolysis, palladium © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2017, 49, A–R ration  of  polysubstituted  aromatic  rings.  A  palladium-me- diated cyclisation together with a thermal approach for the formation of functionalised aromatic rings are compared. In 2006, model studies were developed that could be ap- plied  to  the  synthesis  of  lactonamycin  (1,  Figure  1).  Other interesting  fused  heterocyclic  and  carbocyclic  fused  ring systems could also be formed under the cyclisation condi- tions.10 Initially, a tin-mediated radical cyclisation had been en- visioned to convert amide 2 into the tetracycle 3. Early in- vestigations, however, led to the unexpected tetracycle 4 in 14% yield when the alkenyl bromide 2 was treated with tri- n-butyltin hydride and AIBN in refluxing benzene (Scheme 1).10

Thermal degradation studies were undertaken to deter- mine  the  stability  of  alkenyl  bromide  2.  Thus,  in  the  ab- sence  of  the  tin  hydride,  substrate  2  provided  lactam  4  in improved  yields  for  almost  all  of  the  investigated  solvents (Table 1). It  was  hy- pothesised  that  the  dimethylamine  produced  during  the decomposition  of  DMF  scavenged  hydrobromic  acid  pro- duced during the reaction. Based upon this hypothesis and Corey’s work on gibberellic acid,11 we decided to investigate the use of an acid trap. When 1,2-epoxyhexane was added to the reaction mixture, the tetracyclic product 4 was iso- lated in an improved yield of 76% (Scheme 2).10 We have since shown that the core of the antibiotic lac- tonamycin can be constructed in one synthetic operation in 73% yield from amide 8 using this strategy (Scheme 3).12 Of key importance in the synthesis of the cyclisation substrate Scheme 1   Unexpected thermal cyclisation during studies on the syn- thesis of lactonamycin Table 1   Decomposition Studies Scheme 2   Unexpected cyclisation to provide 4 1,2-epoxyhexane toluene reflux Bu3SnH, AIBN benzene, reflux © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2017, 49, A–R

is the use of the Knochel–Hauser base13 which provided 8 in 60% yield from aldehyde 6. The use of tert-butyl bromide, a neutral proton source, in the workup was also important to the  success  of  this  reaction;  other  proton  sources  had  ad- verse effects on the yield. Further  investigations  to  extend  our  original  findings were  carried  out  (Scheme  4).9,14  Accordingly,  both  the amide  10  and  ester  11  cyclisation  precursors  cyclised  to their respective furan products 12 and 13. There is, howev- er,  a  significant  difference  in  the  rate  of  reaction  between the  two  substrates.  This  difference  in  the  rate  of  reaction can be rationalised by considering the relative populations of  the  reactive  conformers:  there  is  a  lower  population  of the cisoid conformer for the ester than for the amide. Thus  far,  we  have  used  ester  and  amide  substrates  for the cyclisation reaction. In view of the importance of fused all-carbon  rings  in  chemical  research,  we  examined  the possibility of using our cascade sequence for the formation of  functionalised  steroid  mimics;  for  this  purpose,  the  ke- tone substrate 18 was prepared (Scheme 5). Conversion of the known alcohol 1415 into ether 15 proceeded smoothly with  sodium  hydride  and  2,3-dibromopropene.  The  silyl protecting group was removed with TBAF and the resulting alcohol 16 was oxidised under Swern conditions to provide Scheme 3   Thermal cyclisation to form the core of lactonamycin Scheme 4   Synthesis of annulated furans from acyclic precursors 1,2-epoxyhexane toluene reflux TMPMgCl⋅LiCl toluene, –10 °C

Addition of lithium (trimethylsilyl)acetylide to 17 formed, after workup, a propargylic alcohol, which was then  oxidised  with  Dess–Martin  periodinane  to  form  ke- tone 18. In boiling toluene, the ketone precursor 18 cyclised over 4 days to form cyclopentenone 19 in 62% yield (Scheme 6). Alkyne 20 was also formed in 11% yield during the reaction through protodesilylation of the starting material due to the prolonged heating. To  suppress  the  formation  of  alkyne  20,  microwave heating was investigated. As expected, the shorter reaction time resulted in suppressed formation of the alkyne for all solvents investigated. The reaction duration in toluene was substantially reduced from 96 hours to 2 hours for a compa- rable yield (Table 2, entry 3). DMF, acetonitrile and DCE all provided product 19 in a marginally lower yield than tolu- ene.  In  line  with  our  previous  results  (Table  1,  entry  6), DMSO  caused  complete  decomposition  of  the  cyclisation substrate.  Given  the  more  favourable  volatility  and  micro- wave absorption properties of DCE when compared to tolu- ene,16 a higher temperature run was conducted. Cyclisation of the ketone substrate 18 at 200 °C provided the expected product 19 in an improved 81% yield (Table 2, entry 8). We had previously prepared the homologue of the cycli- sation substrate, 21, from 5-hexyn-1-ol using the chemistry described in Scheme 5. Unfortunately, after 4 days in boiling toluene there was no evidence of the cyclised product 22 by 1H NMR spectroscopy. With microwave conditions in hand, the cyclisation of 21 was reinvestigated at the higher tem- perature of 200 °C, with no success (Scheme 7). This result can  be  rationalised  by  considering  the  increase  in  the  de- grees of freedom of ketone 21 relative to the successful sub- strate 18. Notably, reaction of the dioxolane 23, prepared by protection of 18, was also unsuccessful under both conven- tional and microwave heating. With  optimised  microwave  conditions  in  hand  for  the synthesis  of  annulated  furan  19,  the  synthesis  of  pyrrole and  thiophene  analogues  was  investigated.  The  previously prepared alcohol 1415 was chosen as a convenient point to form the amine and sulfide examples. When  the  substrates were  heated  in  a  microwave  reactor,  the  expected  pyrrole 33 and thiophene 34 products were formed in 61% and 58% yield, respectively (Scheme 10). Scheme 8   Preparation of the nitrogen derivative 28 of ether 15 Scheme 9   Preparation of the sulfur derivative 30 of ether 15 Scheme 10   Microwave synthesis of annulated pyrrole 33 and thio- phene 34 © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2017, 49, A–R Multiple  pathways  have  been  proposed  to  account  for this  transformation  (Scheme  11).9  The  first  step  of  the mechanistic proposal can be divided into either a concerted or stepwise pathway. In the concerted pathway, the labelled precursor 35 proceeds directly in one step via a propargylic ene  reaction  to  the  alkenyl  allene  36,  which  can  then  un- dergo  a  Diels–Alder  cyclisation  to  provide  the  observed product 37. A stepwise mechanism may also account for the formation of alkenyl allene 36, proceeding via the diradical 38. The diradical 38 abstracts a deuteron to give the vicinal diradical  39.  Further  rearrangement  of  this  intermediate, followed  by  cyclisation  and  radical–radical  recombination would provide product 37.

The  two  distinct  pathways  leading  to  either  36  or  38 were  proposed  after  comparing  the  mechanism  of  our transformation  to  the  ene  reaction.  For  a  number  of  de- cades it has been suggested that the ene reaction exists on the interface between concerted and stepwise mechanisms, with specific examples to support both proposals.17 Recent computational  experiments  on  the  ene  reaction,  however, have provided evidence for a one-step asynchronous mech- anism,  where  the  carbon–carbon  bond  formation  is  more advanced  than  the  hydrogen  transfer,  for  a  range  of  sub- strates.18 Studies on the related Schmittel cyclisation19 also provides some insight into the mechanism of our transfor- mation.  Early  computational  studies  by  Musch  and  Engels suggested that the Schmittel cyclisation may follow either a concerted  or  stepwise  pathway  depending  on  the  sub- strate.20  Singleton  and  co-workers  also  showed  that  the mechanism of the cyclisation was substrate dependent, but their studies pointed to a more complex mechanistic phe- nomenon.21  Instead  of  dividing  the  mechanism  into  con- certed  and  stepwise  pathways,  Singleton’s  group  demon- strated that there is a single transition state that leads to ei- Scheme 11   Proposed mechanism for the observed cyclisation of deu- terium-labelled thermolysis precursor 35 . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C

ther  the  concerted  product  or  the  diradical  intermediate, giving  rise  to  a  bifurcating  reaction  pathway.22  After  early kinetic  isotope  experimental  observations  supporting  a stepwise mechanism,23 Schmittel and co-workers later sup- ported  this  concept  with  their  own  computational  experi- ments.24  We  propose  that  our  transformation  may  exhibit the  complex  mechanistic  behaviour  seen  for  both  the  ene reaction  and  Schmittel  cyclisations,  based  upon  our  own previously reported observations. In a previous publication, it was shown that the replacement of protons with deuteri- um led to a threefold decrease in the rate of reaction.9 Fur- thermore, the introduction of radical traps did not lead to the expected trapped products. These observations are con- sistent  with  the  concerted  mechanism  suggested  by  other groups working in this area.25,26 As a counterpoint to these observations,  the  unusual  formation  of  compound  42  in  a 30% yield from ketone 41 and the isolation of byproduct 44 from  the  cyclisation  of  43  have  been  attributed  to  radical mechanisms (Scheme 12).9

Concurrent with our studies on the synthesis of lactona- mycin  and  related  compounds,  a  palladium-assisted  cas- cade cyclisation of substituted furans was also being inves- tigated  (Scheme  13).  We  have  previously  shown  that  car- bon-centered  radicals  can  add  to  furans  to  provide substituted  cyclopentenes  through  a  fragmentation  se- quence. For example, alkenyl bromide 48 was heated in tol- uene in the presence of tri-n-butyltin hydride and AIBN to give the bicycle 49 in 51% yield.27 This mechanism involves a  radical  fragmentation  of  the  furan  ring  before  a  [2+2+2] electrocyclisation provides the aromatic ring. In later work, we demonstrated that sulfone 50 can also undergo a radi- Scheme 12   The unusual cyclisations of ketone 41 and alkyne 43 1,2-epoxyhexane toluene reflux 1,2-epoxyhexane toluene reflux © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2017, 49, A–R cal-mediated cyclisation with concomitant furan fragmen- tation to afford the tricycle 51, albeit in a reduced yield of 11%.28 In an effort to improve the yield of this process, we pre- pared  ether  46  for  a  palladium-mediated  cyclisation (Scheme 14). Aldehyde 53 was prepared from furan 52 by an  acid-catalysed  Michael  addition  with  acrolein.  Treat- ment of the aldehyde with ethynylmagnesium bromide and protection of the resultant alcohol gave alkyne 54. Propar- gyl  alcohol  55  was  formed  and  then  allylated  with  2,3-di- bromopropene  to  furnish  the  cyclisation  precursor  46  for the palladium studies.

Alkenyl bromide 46 was heated in the presence of palla- dium(II),  providing  the  tricyclic  ketone  47  in  28%  yield (Scheme 15). This finding was remarkable as the precedent for a palladium-mediated fragmentation of furan was limit- ed. The only example at the time of this research was com- pleted by Grimaud and co-workers, who showed that a pal- Scheme 13   The palladium-mediated cascade and previous work on  tin-mediated cascades Scheme 14   Preparation of the palladium cyclisation precursor 46 hydroquinone AcOH, H2O microwave, 130 °C . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C ladium-mediated fragmentation was a convenient means of tandem  ring  closure  and  formation  α,β-unsaturated  alde- hydes.29  In  contrast  to  Grimaud’s  work,  which  featured  a single ring closure, we were able to form three rings in one pot.  Further  examples  of  palladium-mediated  cyclisation and concomitant furan fragmentation have since been dis- closed.30 Notably, the yield, 28%, for the palladium-mediat- ed domino reaction was an improvement on the previously investigated tin radical procedure. Additional examples were prepared from alcohol 55 fol- lowing  the  chemistry  outlined  for  the  thermal  cyclisation precursors  31  and  32  disclosed  earlier  in  this  publication. With the precursors in hand, the palladium cyclisation frag- mentation sequence was completed, resulting in the forma- tion of the expected aromatic products 59 and 60 from di- ester  56  and  amine  57,  respectively  (Scheme  16).  The  sul- fide  58,  however,  unexpectedly  yielded  cyclopentadiene derivative 61 as the sole product. In this case, it is also nota- ble that the sulfide oxidised under the reaction conditions to provide the sulfone.

In the case of the ether precursor 46, initial analysis of the  reaction  mixture  showed  two  major  products,  but  on continued  heating  under  reflux  one  product  diminished and  ketone  47  was  isolated  as  the  sole  product.  Based  on Scheme 15   Palladium-mediated cascade reaction of 46 Scheme 16   Other examples of palladium-mediated reactions © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2017, 49, A–R our  observations,  it  is  proposed  that  all  examples  proceed via  a  cyclopentadiene  intermediate,  isolated  as  the  sole product  for  sulfide  58.  The  cyclopentadiene  (e.g.,  66)  will then undergo ring expansion and aromatisation to give the bis-annulated product (Scheme 17). In the case of the sul- fide,  further  ring  expansion  is  prevented  due  to  increased ring strain induced by the presence of the sulfone moiety. In order to avoid the use of metallic reagents in our cy- clisation reactions and to attempt to improve the yields of the cyclised products, we investigated the thermal chemis- try of these substrates. Heating substrate 46 in the absence of  palladium  unfortunately  yielded  only  starting  material after 2 hours (Scheme 18). The transformation was also at- tempted at 200 °C in a microwave reactor, without success. Given  our  successful  use  of  diyne  systems  in  our  ap- proach to lactonamycin (Scheme 3), we decided to replace the bromoalkene with an alkyne to provide the new cycli- sation substrate 68 (Scheme 19). This was accomplished in good yield from the previously synthesised propargyl alco- hol  55  (Scheme  14).  In  this  new  approach,  the  furan  ring will  be  acting  as  the  dienophile  before  the  fragmentation sequence to give the tricyclic product 69.

Scheme 17   Proposed mechanistic pathway for the formation of poly- substituted benzene rings Scheme 18   Thermolysis of the palladium precursor 46 . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C Gratifyingly, when alkyne 68 was heated in DMF under microwave irradiation, the pentasubstituted benzene deriv- ative  69  was  isolated  in  45%  yield  (Scheme  20).31  We  pro- posed  that  the  mechanism  for  this  cyclisation  follows  the same  pathway  as  for  the  earlier  thermal  cyclisations (Scheme  11)  to  give  an  alkenyl  allene  intermediate  70, which then undergoes a Diels–Alder cycloaddition with the furan  moiety.  Fragmentation  of  71,  followed  by  oxidation, leads to the pentasubstituted benzene core of 69 (Scheme 21). Early investigations on this theme explored the effect of substitution  on  the  furan  ring  (Scheme  22).  Thus,  it  was possible to prepare aldehyde 76 from the monosubstituted furan 73 and ethyl ketone 77 from the ethyl-substituted fu- ran  74.  The  yield  for  aldehyde  76  was  notably  lower  than both the parent compound and ethyl derivative due to the instability of phenylacetaldehyde 76. Unsurprisingly, meth- yl substitution at the propargylic position, to give precursor 75, leads to an increased cyclisation yield over the unsubsti- tuted parent compound 68.

Alcohol 55 (Scheme 14) was coupled with propiolic acid to give ester 79, which in turn cyclised to give lactone 81 in 62% yield (Scheme 23). Similarly, the carboxylic acid may be formed  from  alkyne  54  (Scheme  14)  and  esterified  with propargyl alcohol to give the isomeric ester 80. Cyclisation of this material under the usual conditions provided lactone 82, also in 62% yield. In  order  to  compare  these  results  to  the  palladium methods,  the  diester  89,  amine  90  and  sulfide  91  cyclisa- tion  precursors  were  also  prepared  (Scheme  25).  The  di- ester and amine cyclisation substrates formed the expected products 92 and 93 in a lower yield than the ether example (Scheme 20). The yields were, however, comparable to the yields for the palladium cyclisation (Scheme 16). In contrast to the palladium methods, sulfide 94, featuring a benzene core, was accessible using the thermal approach. In addition, we demonstrated that the cyclic ether 100 could  also  be  formed  (Scheme  26).  Alcohol  95  was  depro- tonated and reacted with propargyl bromide to give alkyne 97. Propargyl alcohol 98 was formed and ether 99 synthe- sised.  Then,  cyclisation  in  acetonitrile  furnished  tricycle 100. It was proposed that the cyclisation and fragmentation sequence could be performed in an intermolecular fashion using  diyne  102  (Scheme  27). We  have  previously  investi- gated  a  similar  intermolecular  reaction  with  a  number  of dienophiles.33 Thus, thermolysis of diyne 104 results in the Scheme 24   Variation of the alkyne side chain to form hexasubstituted  aromatic rings © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2017, 49, A–R Scheme 25   Cyclisation of diester-, nitrogen- and sulfur-linked diynes Scheme 26   Cyclisation to form the annulated furan 100 and prepara- tion of the precursor 99 Scheme 27   Intermolecular cyclisation of diyne substrates . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C

formation  of  the  corresponding  alkenyl  allene  105  which forms a bicycle upon reaction with allyl alcohol. The adduct is then trapped by the pendant alcohol to provide tricyclic product  106.  Danheiser  has  also  reported  intramolecular– intermolecular examples.26 For these studies, diyne 102 was prepared from butyn- 2-ol (107) through a three-step sequence (Scheme 28). The alcohol  was  first  protected  as  the  silyl  ether  108  before deprotonation and reaction with paraformaldehyde to give propargyl alcohol 109.34 Treatment of the propargyl alcohol with propargyl bromide in the presence of sodium hydride gave ether 102. Heating  ether  102  with  2-methylfuran  in  acetonitrile under microwave conditions did not result in formation of the  intermolecular  aromatic  product  103  (Scheme  29). Spectroscopic  analysis  of  the  crude  material,  however,  re- vealed  a  complex  reaction  profile  that  merited  further  in- vestigation. In the absence of the furan component, it was possible to isolate two new products from this reaction. Furan 110 was isolated in a 40% yield, along with enone 111 (Scheme 30). To  account  for  the  product  distribution,  the  following mechanism was proposed (Scheme 31). Alkenyl allene 112 is  formed,  following  the  previously  discussed  mechanism. Protonation  of  112  results  in  two  regioisomers  113  and 114.  The  Z-alkene  113  aromatises  and  the  silyl  enol  ether 115 is hydrolysed to give the furan product 110. Cyclic ke- tone 111 is formed through electrocyclisation of triene 116. The resultant diene 117 is hydrolysed to form the unsatu- rated ketone 111. Sulfide 119 was also prepared, and then cyclised under identical conditions (Scheme 32). The previously prepared alcohol  109  was  converted  into  thioacetate  118  under Mitsunobu conditions. The thioacetate was cleaved and re- acted with propargyl bromide to give the sulfur precursor 119. This paper has been concerned with our findings on the metal-catalysed versus metal-free domino cyclisation reac- tions  of  a  range  of  alkene-  and  alkyne-containing  sub- strates.
